{{Refimprove|date=May 2011}}
'''Corporate tax in the Netherlands''' deals with the tax payable in [[the Netherlands]] on the profits earned by companies. In general, a Dutch company is subject to 25% corporate tax ("vennootschapsbelasting") on its worldwide profits. However, certain items of income are exempt from tax and certain costs are non-deductible.
==Worldwide profits== A Dutch company is subject to Dutch corporate tax on its worldwide profits, after taking into account tax deductible costs.
==Rate== The 2013 Dutch corporate tax rate was 20% of the taxable income up to and including €200,000, above which the rate is 25%.
==Exemptions== Certain items of income are exempt from Dutch corporate tax. The most important items of income that are exempt are:
* capital gains and dividends derived from qualifying subsidiaries ("participation exemption") * income attributable to a foreign business enterprise ("permanent establishment").
===Participation exemption=== Capital gains, dividends and profit participation loan interest derived from a qualifying subsidiary are fully exempt from corporate tax in the Netherlands ("participation exemption"). A subsidiary qualifies for the Dutch participation exemption when:
* the subsidiary is an active company, and * the Dutch parent company holds an interest of at least 5% of such company.
===Foreign branch=== Any income received by a Dutch company from a foreign branch is exempt from Dutch corporate tax, provided such branch is a permanent establishment or representative.{{cn|date=April 2012}}
==Tax haven== {{see also|Dutch Sandwich (tax avoidance)}} The Netherlands has been known internationally, since at least the 1970s, as a [[tax haven]]. A political debate about this issue started in 1977, when economist and [[Labor Party (Netherlands)|social-democratic]] MP [[Flip de Kam]] published a book about corporations transferring large sums to Caribbean countries without paying Dutch corporate tax. Minister [[Fons van der Stee|Van der Stee]] admitted that the country was internationally known as a tax haven, but refused to act, arguing that the problem could not be solved on a national level alone.<ref name="vn">{{cite newspaper |title=Nederland belastingparadijs, met dank aan de PvdA |newspaper=[[Vrij Nederland]] |first1=Tomas |last1=Vanheste |first2=Map |last2=Oberndorff |url=http://www.vn.nl/nederland-belastingparadijs-met-dank-aan-de-pvda/ |trans-title=The Netherlands a tax haven, thanks to the Labor Party |date=6 August 2013}}</ref> The debate raged for years; in 1986, [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Representative]] [[Willem Vermeend]] estimated that the country's tax service missed some [[Dutch guilder|ƒ]]4 billion per year due to companies such as [[The Rolling Stones]]' holding [[Besloten vennootschap|bv]]'s using the "Caribbean route".{{r|vn}}
Dutch tax laws have brought the country into conflict with the [[European Union]] several times, starting with strong criticism in the 1999 [[Dawn Primarolo|Primarolo]] Report. The Dutch government responded by having a group of high-ranking fiscal experts (known with the [[Ministry of Finance (Netherlands)|Ministry of Finance]] as the "[[Barbapapa]] group") create a smoke screen, changing the appearance of the fiscal system while leaving its structure intact.{{r|vn}}
Starting 2009, the "tax haven" label resurfaced and sparked political controversy when the [[White House]] issued a press release in which the Netherlands was mentioned as tax haven.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taxjustice.nl/?nid=62060|title=The Netherlands a tax haven, a misunderstanding?|publisher=Tax Justice nl|accessdate=21 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2009/05/us_tax_haven_claim_surprises_d.php|title=US tax haven claim surprises Dutch|date=5 May 2009|publisher=DutchNews.nl|accessdate=21 May 2011}}</ref> According to various NGO's the Netherlands "can be seen as an intermediary tax haven for foreign corporations".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://somo.nl/news-en/new-tax-treaty-policy-prejudices-developing-countries/|title=New tax treaty policy prejudices developing countries|date=20 April 2011|publisher=Centre for Research on Multinational Corporations|accessdate=21 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Michielse|first=Geerten|date=24 February 2011|title=Mag het een beetje minder koopman zijn?|publisher=Tijdschrift voor Fiscaal Recht|url=http://www.michielse.com/files/NTFR_2011-379.pdf|language=Dutch}}</ref><ref name="masters">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/oct/19/tax-avoidance-in-netherlands-becomes-focus-of-campaigners |date=19 October 2011 |title=Dutch masters of tax avoidance |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> In February 2013, the Dutch House of Representatives accepted a motion calling on cabinet members to "reject, and where possible in discussions to insist on not mentioning" the qualification of the country as a tax haven; the motion was drafted by MP [[Roland van Vliet]], a former tax advisor with [[Ernst & Young]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper |title=Geert Wilders houdt wél van belastingparadijs Nederland |trans-title=Geert Wilders does love Holland, the tax haven |first=Henk Willem |last=Smits |url=http://www.quotenet.nl/Nieuws/Geert-Wilders-houdt-wel-van-belastingparadijs-Nederland-53310 |date=19 February 2013}}</ref> Economist {{ill|Ewald Engelen|nl}} estimated that at the time of the motion, the state earned some €1.5 billion in tax from €12 thousand billion being transferred through the country annually.<ref>{{cite newspaper |first=Ewald |last=Engelen |title=Nederland is een topplek voor belastingontwijking |trans-title=Holland is a great place for tax avoidance |date=16 February 2013}}</ref>
{{As of|2013}}, the country harbors [[holding company|holding companies]] for various multinationals, participates in more than a hundred bilateral [[tax treaty|tax treaties]], and the various [[#Exemptions|exemptions]] facilitate [[tax avoidance]] by corporations.{{r|vn}}{{r|masters}}
In June 2014 the EU initiated a new investigation relating to the Dutch corporate taxes as part of a [[State aid (European Union)]] case by the Directorate General for Competition. The case was specific to [[Starbucks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-11-14/starbucks-dutch-tax-deal-clashes-with-global-rules-eu|title=Starbucks Unit Swapped Millions of Euros for Roasting Art|publisher=Bloomberg|date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The investigation ended in October 2015, with the EC ordering Starbucks to pay up to €30 million in overdue taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-5880_en.htm|title=Commission decides selective tax advantages for Fiat in Luxembourg and Starbucks in the Netherlands are illegal under EU state aid rules|publisher=European Commission|date=21 October 2015}}</ref> The EC exposed in its decision a legal structure commonly used by companies established in the Netherlands to avoid corporate taxation, the so called Dutch BV-CV structure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibfd.org/IBFD-Products/Journal-Articles/Bulletin-for-International-Taxation/collections/bit/html/bit_2016_03_nl_1.html|title=European Union/Netherlands - Dutch CV-BV Structures: Starbucks-Style Tax Planning and State Aid Rules.|publisher=IBFD|date=11 February 2016}}</ref> In 2017, the EU initiated another [[State aid (European Union)]] investigation into a special deal on corporate taxation between the Dutch public administration and [[IKEA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-17-5343_en.htm |title=State aid: Commission opens in-depth investigation into the Netherlands' tax treatment of Inter IKEA|publisher=European Commission|date=18 December 2017}}</ref>
National and foreign companies known to have special agreements with the Dutch tax service include Starbucks, [[Microsoft]] and [[PostNL]]. A 2015 [[Freedom of information laws by country#Netherlands|FOI]] request by ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' to unearth the agreements failed, because these secret agreements are not centrally administered by the [[Tax and Customs Administration]]; with even the House of Representatives not having access to them.<ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Belastingdienst: geen zicht op deals met bedrijven |trans-title=Tax Administration: no overview of deals with corporations |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/belastingdienst-geen-zicht-op-deals-met-bedrijven~a4168976/ |newspaper=De Volkskrant |date=23 October 2015}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Taxation in the Netherlands]]
